[1
Date: 28 Feb 2001
From: The Pig Disease Information Centre <pdic@bninternet.com>
Source: Media

3 sheep on farm near Dusseldorf, North Rhein Westfalia, imported into
Germany from the United Kingdom (UK) found to have a low level Foot and
Mouth Disease (FMD) antibodies. 2000 sheep imported from the UK have beeen
destroyed. The UK CVO says the antibodies are probably not significant.
More outbreaks [are expected in [the UK - probably in Wales and SW of
country where many herds are under investigation.
***
Date: 27 Feb 2001
Source: BBC and MAFF

Outbreaks 19-22 involve sheep at a farm in Llangowan, Herefordshire; a farm
at Paincastle near Hay on Wye, Powys, Wales; a farm at Felindre near
Newtown, Powys; an abattoir at Great Harwood, near Preston, Lancashire. The
cases are probably related to sheep marketing movements prior to movement ban.
Also, 30 000 sheep have been destroyed in France
Outbreaks 23-24 have been confirmed on sheep farm in Stonesby, near Melton
Mowbray, Leicestershire and at another farm in Highampton, Devon.
Outbreaks 25-26 confirmed: farm in Essex, farm in Warwickshire
Outbreak in Co. Armagh, N. Ireland is strongly suspected. 200 sheep were
imported from the UK market, only 20 have been traced. There are concerns
animals may have been moved into the Republic of Ireland. 1300 sheep were
destroyed there already which had been imported from Devon.
-足
The Pig Disease Information Centre
<pdic@btinternet.com>
