[5
Date: 28 Feb 2001
From: M. Cosgriff <mcosgriff@hotmail.com>
Sources: The Scotsman, 28 Feb 2001 [edited
<http://www.thescotsman.co.uk/index.cfm?id=50778>

The search for the source of the Foot-and Mouth Disease-epidemic which is
paralyzing Britain has switched to a row of Chinese restaurants in
Newcastle and a number of schools located around the city. The Scotsman can
reveal some of the waste food which was turned into pigswill, and used by
the 2 farms in Northumbria believed to be at the center of the outbreak,
was collected from up to 10 Chinese restaurants in Stowell Street, in
Newcastle's China Town.
Inspectors from the Ministry of Agriculture contacted farmer Bobby Waugh
yesterday to demand a list of suppliers of the waste food he collected to
feed to his pigs at his farm at Heddon-on-the-Wall in Northumberland. Mr
Waugh and his immediate farming neighbor, Jimmy Brown, jointly turn waste
food, collected in Newcastle, into pigswill at a shared processing plant
located on Mr Brown's farm. All animals at both farms have now been
destroyed, even though FMD has only been confirmed on the farm run by Mr
Waugh and his brother Ronnie. It has been identified as the original source
of the outbreak.
Mr Brown is known as one of the largest collectors of waste food for
pigswill in Newcastle, with most being picked up free from the city's
Chinese community. Mr Waugh also collects waste food from a number of
schools in Sunderland and Gateshead and is supplied by one hotel, which he
refused to name yesterday. It is thought any of these suppliers could be a
source of the disease, but it is believed there is a high probability
people who work in Chinese restaurants may have traveled abroad recently.
The disease does not affect humans, but can be carried across borders on
their hands, feet and clothing.
Mr Waugh said he and his neighbor were licensed to create pigswill on Mr
Brown's premises. "We boil the waste food at 93 degrees [C for 4 hours.
Those are the rules and everything is sterilized. The tanks are tested
every 3 months by the ministry to check they are working properly." He said
he did not believe the outbreak had started in pigswill. "This all started
because somebody claimed the food came from the airport. But that's wrong.
It is illegal to collect swill from ports or airports."
Mr Brown could not be contacted for comment yesterday. His wife, however,
insisted batches of pigswill were kept separate. "We have had the tests
back now," she added. "And foot-and-mouth wasn't confirmed. It could have
been incubating in the animals. You don't know that."
Inspectors from Newcastle City Council were yesterday visiting Chinese
restaurants in Stowell Street and advising their owners to find new
arrangements for disposing of waste food. The practice of having food
collected by pig farmers is popular because it is free of charge and saves
payments having to be made to commercial waste collectors.
Newcastle International Airport yesterday confirmed all their waste food
does not re-enter the food chain and is taken away for destruction by
licensed contractors.
A spokesman for the Ministry of Agriculture confirmed the supply of
pigswill was being looked into. "It is one of a number of lines we're
pursuing. We have asked local authorities to investigate on our behalf."
